{"title_page": "Joshua D. Rauh", "text_new": "{{short description|American economist}}\n'''Joshua D. Rauh''' is an American economist.\n\nRauh is currently the Principal Chief Economist of the [[Council of Economic Advisers]]. He is also serving as the Director of Research at the Hoover Institution and is the Ormond Family Professor of Finance at [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoover.org/press-releases/senior-fellow-joshua-d-rauh-named-presidents-council-economic-advisers|title=Senior Fellow Joshua D. Rauh Named To The President's Council Of Economic Advisers|website=Hoover Institution|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> He graduated with a B.A. in economics, [[Magna cum Laude|magna cum laude]] with distinction, from [[Yale University]] in 1996 and received a Ph.D. in economics from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/joshua-d-rauh|title=Joshua D. Rauh|website=Stanford Graduate School of Business|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBefore becoming a Stanford Professor, Rauh has formerly taught at University of Chicago\u2019s Booth School of Business (2004\u20139) and the [[Kellogg School of Management]] (2009\u201312).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/~rauh/about.html|title=About|website=web.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> Rauh studies corporate investment, business taxation, government pension liabilities, and investment management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoover.org/profiles/joshua-d-rauh|title=Joshua D. Rauh|website=Hoover Institution|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> He has published numerous journal articles and was awarded the 2006 Brattle Prize for the outstanding research paper on corporate finance published in the Journal of Finance for his paper \u201cInvestment and Financing Constraints: Evidence from the Funding of Corporate Pension Plans.\u201d In 2011 he won the [[Smith Breeden Prize]] for the outstanding research paper on capital markets, published in the Journal of Finance, for his paper \u201cPublic Pension Promises: How Big Are They and What Are they Worth?\u201d coauthored with Robert Novy-Marx.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/joshua-d-rauh|title=Joshua D. Rauh|website=Stanford Graduate School of Business|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> His other writings include \u201cEarnings Manipulation, Pension Assumptions and Managerial Investment Decisions,\u201d coauthored with Daniel Bergstresser and [[Mihir Desai]], which won the Barclays Global Investor Best Symposium Paper from the [[European Finance Association]] and appeared in the [[Quarterly Journal of Economics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/joshua-d-rauh|title=Joshua D. Rauh|website=Stanford Graduate School of Business|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> Other work has appeared in the [[The Review of Financial Studies|Review of Financial Studies]], the [[Journal of Financial Economics]], and the [[Journal of Political Economy]].\n\nRauh\u2019s research on state and local pension systems in the United States has received national media coverage in outlets such as the Wall Street Journal, the New York Times, the Financial Times, and The Economist.\n\nHe was appointed to the position of principal chief economist by President [[Donald Trump]] and began his term on November 4, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siepr.stanford.edu/news/sieprs-josh-rauh-joins-council-economic-advisers|title=SIEPR's Josh Rauh joins Council of Economic Advisers {{!}} SIEPR|website=siepr.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/joshua-d-rauh\n* https://web.stanford.edu/~rauh/\n* https://www.hoover.org/profiles/joshua-d-rauh\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rauh, Joshua D.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American economists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American economist}}\n'''Joshua D. Rauh''' is an American economist.\n\nRauh is currently the Principal Chief Economist of the [[Council of Economic Advisers]]. He is also serving as the Director of Research at the Hoover Institution and is the Ormond Family Professor of Finance at [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoover.org/press-releases/senior-fellow-joshua-d-rauh-named-presidents-council-economic-advisers|title=Senior Fellow Joshua D. Rauh Named To The President's Council Of Economic Advisers|website=Hoover Institution|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> He graduated with a B.A. in economics, [[Magna cum Laude|magna cum laude]] with distinction, from [[Yale University]] in 1996 and received a Ph.D. in economics from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/faculty-research/faculty/joshua-d-rauh|title=Joshua D. Rauh|website=Stanford Graduate School of Business|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBefore becoming a Stanford Professor, Rauh has formerly taught at University of Chicago\u2019s Booth School of Business (2004\u20139) and the [[Kellogg School of Management]] (2009\u201312).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/~rauh/about.html|title=About|website=web.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> Rauh studies corporate investment, business taxation, government pension liabilities, and investment management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoover.org/profiles/joshua-d-rauh|title=Joshua D. Rauh|website=Hoover Institution|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> He has published numerous journal articles a